liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Earlier we mentioned the UN Security Council voted in favour of calling for urgent and extended humanitarian pauses in the Israel-Gaza war. The resolution calls for a pause for a "sufficient number of days" to allow humanitarian aid access. But the Israeli UN ambassador says the resolution is "disconnected from reality and is meaningless". "Regardless of what the Council decides, Israel will continue acting according to int'l law while the Hamas terrorists will not even read the resolution at all, let alone abide by it," Gildan Erdan says on social media platform X. Mr Erdan voiced his disappointment the council did not mention Hamas's October 7 terrorist attack in their resolution before reiterating Israel's intention. "It will not happen. Israel will continue to act until Hamas is destroyed and the hostages are returned."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Israeli UN ambassador  calls UN Security Council resolution 'meaningless'

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The United Nations Security Council has overcome a deadlock in its search for a resolution to the Israel-Gaza war. It called for urgent and extended humanitarian pauses in fighting between Israel and Palestinian Hamas militants in the Gaza Strip for a "sufficient number of days" to allow humanitarian aid access. The 15-member council saw four unsuccessful attempts to take action last month, to adopt a resolution that also calls for the immediate and unconditional release of all hostages held by Hamas. The United States, Russia and Britain, who are council veto-powers, abstained from the vote on the resolution drafted by Malta. The remaining 12 members voted in favour. Russia failed in a last minute bid to amend the resolution to include a call for an immediate humanitarian truce leading to a cessation of hostilities. The council stalemate has largely been centered on whether to call for a humanitarian pause or a ceasefire. A pause is generally considered less formal and shorter than a ceasefire, which has to be agreed by the warring parties. The United States has backed pauses, while Russia has pushed for a ceasefire. The resolution also does not condemn the actions of Hamas — a point of contention for Israel's ally, the United States, and Britain. The council called "for urgent and extended humanitarian pauses and corridors throughout the Gaza Strip for a sufficient number of days to enable … the full, rapid, safe, and unhindered humanitarian access." The resolution demands compliance with international law, specifically the protection of civilians, especially children. It also calls on all parties not to deprive civilians in Gaza of basic services and humanitarian aid needed for their survival, welcomes the initial, limited deliveries of aid but calls for that to be increased. Reuters

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has declared there is no place in Gaza his forces will not reach, after his troops stormed the besieged Al-Shifa hospital in Gaza. Witnesses inside Al-Shifa say that Israeli troops went from building to building, searched between different departments including the basement of the surgical ward and questioned patients, Middle East correspondent Allyson Horn reports. "Witnesses there have described the situation as tense but calm. There has been no reports of any shooting or gunfire inside those hospital buildings and no reports of anybody injured", she said. The Gaza ministry of health has said that the patients who were questioned were terrified and that it's unacceptable for Israel to be operating inside a civilian hospital. "Shifa hospital is still besieged. The occupation soldiers are still on the ground floor and the bedroom floor. They are searching employees, civilians, even the injured and the patients", Dr Mohammad Zaqout from the Gazan health ministry said. "Some of them were unclothed and placed in dehumanising and miserable conditions." In a statement, Israel said its troops were engaged in a gun battle with Hamas militants upon entering the hospital, and that several of those militants were killed. Israel has maintained that its raid is a targeted operation specifically aimed at Hamas infrastructure and weaponry, which the Israeli Defense Force claim to have found inside the hospital, but did not specify where. The IDF released footage of the weaponry they claim to have found but the ABC was not able to independently verify the video. Hamas has maintained that it does not use the hospital to shield its operations. Watch the full report below.

The sectors trading slightly lower are academic and educational services (-0.4%), real estate (-0.4%), technology (-0.3%), basic materials (-0.3%), and financials (-0.1%). liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: There's been a lot of talk this morning around the federal government's plans to scrap funding for 82 "high risk" infrastructure projects around the country, in response to a review of infrastructure funding. The names and locations of those 82 projects will be made public later today when Infrastructure Minister Catherine King releases the government's response to the independent review. The review found the existing list of projects for the decade could not be delivered under the current $120 billion budget, with some of those projects were found to have lacked merit and strategic rationale, and others were deemed to have been allocated funding without a complete business case. Ms King says the budget for delivering the projects remains, but discontinuing some will allow those remaining to be delivered. Before the list is made public, you can get up to speed on the background of this story from political reporter Nicole Hegarty below:

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: We're about all things employment statistics today, so how likely is it that we could see the jobless rate tick up to 3.7% when the ABS gives its latest update? We know the unemployment rate is an important piece of data for the RBA, but as the dust settles from yesterday's strong wage growth figures, could that add to the central bank's worries, or will they be able to see past the one-off rises from the increase to award wages and the pay rise for aged care workers? Plus, a new survey from NAB has painted a picture of the budget cuts Gen Z are making. It turns out they're dumping streaming services like Netflix and Stan, but keeping their dating apps (yes, really). Our senior business correspondent Peter Ryan discussed all of the above with Thomas Oriti on ABC News Radio earlier this morning — but if you didn't catch it, you can listen in below.
